          "body": "The most theologically dense passage in the chapter is not its largest tribal register but its smallest narrative — seven verses about Ephraim's grief (vv. 20-24). The genealogical descent from Ephraim to Joshua flows normally through five generations until it is suddenly interrupted: 'Ezer and Elead whom the men of Gath who were born in the land killed, because they came down to take their livestock' (v. 21). Two sons, dead. Killed not in battle but in a livestock raid gone catastrophically wrong. Then: 'Their father Ephraim mourned many days, and his relatives came to comfort him' (v. 22). The Chronicler uses the verb aval — the formal mourning term used for Jacob's grief over Joseph (Genesis 37:34) and for Israel's mourning at Sinai (Exodus 33:4). The grief is total and extended. Then — 'he went in to his wife, and she conceived and bore a son, and he named him Beriah, because misfortune had come upon his house' (v. 23). The new son's name carries the tragedy permanently: Beriah means 'in evil' or 'misfortune.' The Chronicler will not let the grief be forgotten or sentimentalized. It is embedded in the name of the next generation."
