          "body": "The territorial summary of Ephraim and Manasseh (vv. 28-29) is the chapter's most directly pastoral element for its first audience. The returning exiles of Ezra-Nehemiah's era faced a concrete question: do we have a legal right to the land our ancestors held? The Chronicler answers with geography. Bethel — where Jacob met God (Genesis 28:10-22). Shechem — where the covenant was renewed under Joshua (Joshua 24:1-27). Gezer — taken by Egypt and given as a wedding gift to Solomon's wife (1 Kings 9:16-17). Beth-shean, Taanach, Megiddo, Dor — the great strategic cities of the north. These are not random villages. They are the anchor-points of Israel's covenant history. By placing them in Ephraim and Manasseh's territorial portfolio, the Chronicler asserts that the Josephite tribes' claim to their land was not abrogated by the exile — it was suspended. The register exists to reconstitute what the Babylonians disrupted. The chapter's closing summary — 'these lived the sons of Joseph the son of Israel' (v. 29) — is not historical reportage. It is a land deed backed by the authority of the covenant."
