        "body": "The opening thirteen verses of 1 Chronicles 7 cover four tribes: Issachar (vv. 1-5), Benjamin (vv. 6-12), and Naphtali (v. 13). The variation in detail is immediately striking — Issachar receives five verses and a total of 87,000; Benjamin receives seven verses with three sub-clan totals (22,034 + 20,200 + 17,200 = 59,434); Naphtali receives one verse with four names and no count at all. The unevenness reflects the reality that the Chronicler worked with pre-existing source documents of varying completeness, not that he valued some tribes more than others. What is theologically constant across all three treatments is the fixed formula: gibbor chayil ('mighty man of valor') and yachas ('enrolled by genealogy').\n\nThe military framing is not incidental. The Numbers 1 census was explicitly a military muster — 'all who are able to go out to war in Israel, you and Aaron shall number them by their armies' (Numbers 1:3). The Chronicler's genealogical section serves a similar function for the post-exilic community. By registering each tribe's warrior capacity, he asserts that Israel is not a decimated, demoralized refugee population but a reconstituting nation with legitimate military and civic standing. The 87,000 total for all Issachar families (v. 5) is particularly significant — it is the largest single tribal total in the chapter and testifies to Issachar's demographic vitality.\n\nThe Naphtali entry (v. 13) deserves attention precisely because of its brevity. Four names — Jahziel, Guni, Jezer, Shallum — with the identifying note 'the sons of Bilhah.' Bilhah was Rachel's handmaid, given to Jacob when Rachel was barren (Genesis 30:3-8). The Chronicler's inclusion of the concubine-born tribes without stigma or subordinate classification reflects a theology of covenant inclusivity: every line descending from Jacob, regardless of the mother's status, stands equally within the covenant community. This directly parallels the Manasseh entry in v. 14, where Asriel is born of an Aramean concubine — the mixed-descent line is registered without apology.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Gibbor chayil* — *gibbor* (mighty warrior) + *chayil* (strength, valor, capability) — is the precise honorific given to Boaz in Ruth 2:1 and to Gideon in Judges 6:12; its application here to entire tribal contingents elevates the corporate identity of each tribe to the standard of Israel's most celebrated individuals. *Yachas* (to enroll by genealogy) is the technical term for genealogical registration in Ezra-Nehemiah (Ezra 2:62; Nehemiah 7:5, 64) — the Chronicler uses it here to signal that these registers carry the same legal weight as the post-exilic community lists."
